```
Does it clear `ctx->call_controls`? No!
So when the new `kdamond` thread starts, it executes `kdamond_call(ctx, false)` in its main loop.
`kdamond_call()` splices `ctx->call_controls` and processes them!
So the new `kdamond` will process the `control` struct that was left in the list.
But wait! The `control` struct was allocated on the stack of the thread that called `damon_lru_sort_commit_inputs_store` which was blocked on `wait_for_completion`!
Wait, if it was blocked on `wait_for_completion`, it's still alive! The stack is still valid!
So the new kdamond will process it, call `control->fn`, and then `complete(&control->completion)`.
The `commit_inputs` store thread will then wake up, return, and its stack will be unwound.
Is there a memory corruption? No, because the thread was blocked the whole time, keeping the stack valid!

BUT wait! Is it possible for `wait_for_completion` to return WITHOUT the completion being signaled?
No, `wait_for_completion` ONLY returns when `complete()` is called. It doesn't return on signals or timeouts.
So the stack frame is guaranteed to be valid as long as `wait_for_completion` is blocked.
Wait, but what if the kdamond thread NEVER starts again?
Then the `commit_inputs` sysfs write hangs forever. This is a denial of service (unkillable process in D state).
And if someone starts kdamond again, it recovers.

